{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"Answers will vary.

Wildfire can cause some positive impacts, especially for ecosystems. For example, fire can rejuvenate old forests by opening space for new saplings to grow. It can convert organic matter to ash and increase the level of important nutrients such as phosphorus, potassium, calcium, and magnesium in the soil. Some trees, such as the lodgepole pine, require fire for their seed to open and begin to sprout.
","teacherTip":"Wildfires are a natural part of many ecosystems. Many forests and grasslands need fire to initiate new growth cycles of young vegetation. Indigenous people around the world are experts when it comes to fire management. They expertly use fire to control the amount of burnable vegetation on the ground so the risk of a massive wildfire is reduced (see <a href="https://www.klc.org.au/indigenous-fire-management" target="_blank">Australian Indigenous Fire Management</a>). The U.S. has recently adopted the idea of prescribed burns for these very reasons. ","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}
